 his people are referred to as ‘Aiyy kin’ (the deity’s relatives). Naturally, too, on account of his vital role (in saving his people from destruction and oblivion by evil, many-legged, fire-breathing, one-armed, one legged Cyclops-type monsters – the Devil’s relatives representing all possible sins), he is depicted not only as strong, but also a handsome, remarkably athletic and incredibly brave and well-built man ‘as swift as an arrow’, but also with an uncontrollable temper when required.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEpic poetry, Yakut -- Translations into english. 0aEpic poetry, YakutvTranslations into English. 0aPoetry -- 19th century -- Criticism and interpretation. 0aPoetry -- 20th century -- Criticism and interpretation. 4aAsian Studies. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aSiberia. 4aTraditional stories, myths and fairy tales. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ademons.  aheroes.  amonsters.  aunesco masterpiece of oral history.  ayakut epic.1 aDybo, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvanov, Vasily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakhodkina, Alina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPukhov, Innokenty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066278808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311102376240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781898823377?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781898823377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781898823377/original  a978-3-11-066278-8  Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c200